Q: Fastest triangulation algorithm with holes? A: <p>I understand that this post is very old now, but for anyone who might be still lurking ... I've very recently added Constrained Delaunay Triangulation to my <a href="https://github.com/AngusJohnson/Clipper2" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><strong>Clipper2 Library</strong></a>.</p>
<pre><code>#include &quot;clipper2/clipper.h&quot;
#include &quot;../../Utils/clipper.svg.h&quot;
#include &quot;../../Utils/clipper.svg.utils.h&quot;

  PathsD subject{ 
    MakePathD({61, 142, 51, 65, 131, 68, 199, 20, 380, 26, 438, 68, 554, 53, 513, 209, 560, 
      290, 549, 483, 446, 542, 370, 527, 278, 580, 141, 554, 106, 446, 20, 354, 21, 252, 102, 214}),  
    MakePathD({200, 208, 297, 218, 240, 97, 170, 115, 206, 148}),
    MakePathD({432, 130, 387, 171, 364, 281, 423, 321, 420, 232, 435, 130}),
    MakePathD({333, 432, 410, 423, 333, 378}),
    MakePathD({193, 276, 136, 287, 197, 449, 268, 335, 232, 292})
  };
PathsD sol;
Triangulate(subject, 0, sol, true);
DisplayAsSvg(&quot;test.svg&quot;, nullptr, nullptr, &amp;sol);
</code></pre>
